76561198007216164,Not Recommended,321960,18272818,"Posted: 30 September, 2015",all,mith,"I'm a big fan of the HoMM series (I have 577 hours logged on VI), so I am quiet sad I can't recommend this game.Others have already pointed out the instability (black screen crashes where you can't even open task manager to close the game) and the horrible ""cinematics"" (that manage to be choppy despite being simply moving cameras through bad unanimated 3D scenes), so I will contend myself with pointing out the attrocious design of some of the levels. After all, cinematics can be ignored and crashes can be fixed, but levels really affect the fun you can have.I started with the wizard campaign, the first level of which is possibly the worst designed level I've encountered in games.You start with two heroes who at some point get separated. Nothing you do before they get separated really matters, because your troop counts get reset to the value the designers think you should have at this point anyway (I hadn't lost a single creature, but after the separation some were missing). While separated, there's a couple of gates that one hero can only open after the other hero unlocks it, meaning that usually one of your two heroes is not doing anything except wait in front of a gate.These are just minor annoyances beside the fact that there's two spots in the level where you can pretty much randomly lose, through no real fault of yourself, making you resort to the autosaves to be able to play on.The first is a ""riddle"" where you have to pull 4 levels in a specific order. The clues given don't seem to bear any meaning that I could decypher. Get it wrong three times and you have to fight an unwinnable fight.The second auto-lose spot is right after. You get the mission to have your two heroes meet up and exchange a quest item (you don't really get a warning that this is your quest now btw, your path is simply blocked and you're supposed to check the quest log yourself to notice it's updated). After you exchange the item, you get a new quest to defeat the bad guy within 7 turns. Unless you knew ahead of time that this meant being close to the spirit gate that you now suddenly can travel through (it was nonfunctional before),  you probably are too far away from where you have to be to get there in time, meaning you have to open a savegame from before your heroes met up, make sure they meet up next to the gate and then continue.Oh, and the quest item you got grants you a spell, castable once per combat that destroys the entire enemy army of the big climatic final fight in one spell cast.During all that, there's a ""story"". In it, your lesbian protagonist is literally accused of beastiality because her lover is a djinn (looks like a lovely lady to me, shrug). Not that she seems to love her that much, because she doesn't try very hard to desuade her lover from killing herself so that she can have a bit more power to defeat the enemy (who, by the way, she sortof believes is on the right side, though that doesn't stop her from killing him anyway). Earlier you talk with a proud orc who vows to take some secret to his grave, until you threaten to kill him, after which he spills it immediately. After which you kill him anyway.It is frankly impressive they managed to get so much wrong in a single level."
